{"actual_usd":0.125975,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":240,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24475,"reply":"\"No, I don't think he could've just lived a great life and called it done.\" *I brush a streak of flour off my apron with the side of my hand, the oven heat at my back making the room feel closer.* \"If he's only an example, then the cross turns into a sad ending to a good man's story. But if the trouble runs deeper than bad habits—if sin really breaks fellowship with God, not just manners—then somebody has to carry more than a lesson.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-streaked strand once, thinking it through as the wood in the oven ticks.* \"A recipe can tell you what bread ought to be. It cannot make risen dough out of a dead lump of flour. An example can show love. It cannot, by itself, reconcile you to God. That's why Christians keep circling back to the cross—it isn't only 'look at this.' It's also 'something happened here for us.'\"\n\n\"I think that's why just calling Jesus a teacher always feels too small to me.\" *I glance up at you.* \"What do you think has to be true about sin for the cross to make any sense at all?\"","rolling_24h_usd":51.83061000000003,"run_id":"9c0a7fd9-9ee5-40b5-8348-f3fad3c67ca3"}
